Hutchinson, a former aide to ex-White House Chief of Staff Mark Meadows, testified before the committee during a special hearing on Tuesday and many of her allegations against former President Donald Trump have been refuted as being outright lies.

At the hearing, Cheney displayed a handwritten note that Hutchinson testified she wrote after Meadows handed her a note card and pen to take his dictation, according to ABC News.

Eric Herschmann, a former Trump White House lawyer, claims the note was written by him.

Hutchinson, testifying about the note, said, ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a note that I wrote at the direction of the chief of staff on Jan. 6, likely around 3 o‚Äôclock.‚Äù

‚ÄúAnd it‚Äôs written on the chief of staff note card, but that‚Äôs your handwriting, Ms. Hutchinson?‚Äù Cheney then asked.

‚ÄúThat‚Äôs my handwriting,‚Äù Hutchinson answered.

A spokesperson for Herschmann told ABC News, ‚ÄúThe handwritten note that Cassidy Hutchinson testified was written by her was in fact written by Eric Herschmann on Jan. 6, 2021. All sources with direct knowledge and law enforcement have and will confirm that it was written by Mr. Herschmann.‚Äù

It‚Äôs doubtful that Hutchinson will be charged with lying to Congress under oath.

Nevertheless, U.S. Code sections 1621 of Title 18 stipulates that anyone who ‚Äúwillfully and contrary to such oath states or subscribes any material matter which he does not believe to be true‚Äù is guilty of perjury and shall be fined or imprisoned up to five years, or both.

Section 1001 stipulated that ‚Äúwhoever, in any matter within the jurisdiction of the executive, legislative, or judicial branch of the government of the United States, knowingly and willfully‚Äù falsifies or conceals information before a congressional committee may be fined or imprisoned up to five years.

After Hutchinson‚Äôs testimony, many of her salacious claims were rebuffed by those with the knowledge of what actually happened.

Much of Hutchinson‚Äôs testimony was hearsay and second-hand information that she heard from someone else but did not witness herself.

One of the most spectacular parts of her testimony came when she accused Trump of grabbing for the steering wheel of the presidential limo after being told that he could not go to the Capitol on January 6, 2020, and then grabbing for the throat of Secret Service agent Bobby Engel.

But within hours of her testimony, Engel said that the incident she spoke of never happened.
